04126nam a22005535i 9780887559303DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875593037 a10.1515/97808875593032doi  a(DE-B1597)664569  a(OCoLC)1198618285  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aHIS0060202bisacsh1 aCoutts, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAuthorized Heritage :bPlace, Memory, and Historic Sites in Prairie Canada /cRobert Coutts. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tLandscapes of Memory in Prairie Canada -- tMemory Hooks: Commemorating Indigenous Cultural Landscapes -- tNational Dreams: Commemorating the Fur Trade in Manitoba -- t“We Came. We Toiled. God Blessed”: Settler Colonialism and Constructing Authenticity -- tContested Space: Commemorating Indigenous Places of Resistance -- tHeritage Place: The Function of Modernity, Gender, and Sexuality -- tHistory, Memory, and the Heritage Discourse -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAuthorized Heritage analyses the history of commemoration at heritage sites across western Canada. Using extensive research from predominantly government records, it argues that heritage narratives are almost always based on national messages that commonly reflect colonial perceptions of the past. Yet many of the places that commemorate Indigenous, fur trade, and settler histories are contested spaces, places such as Batoche, Seven Oaks, and Upper Fort Garry being the most obvious. At these heritage sites, Indigenous views of history confront the conventions of settler colonial pasts and represent the fluid cultural perspectives that should define the shifting ground of heritage space. Robert Coutts brings his many years of experience as a public historian to this detailed examination of heritage sites across the prairies. He shows how the process of commemoration often reflects social and cultural perspectives that privilege a conventional and conservative national narrative. He also examines how class, gender, and sexuality often remain apart from the heritage discourse. Most notably, Authorized Heritage examines how governments became the mediators of what is heritage and, just as significantly, what is not.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryzCanada. 0aHistoric sitesxSocial aspectszManitoba. 0aHistoric sitesxSocial aspectszSaskatchewan. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aMemorialsxSocial aspectszManitoba. 0aMemorialsxSocial aspectszSaskatchewan. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755930340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887559303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887559303/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles